\begin{abstract}
Personal financial planning is a sequential decision problem shaped by income variability, expenditure patterns, liquidity constraints, and long-horizon goals. Conventional tools remain rule-based and weakly adaptive. This paper presents a hybrid multi-agent framework combining structured financial analysis, reinforcement learning for strategy selection, and natural-language explanation. The system integrates specialized agents for risk assessment, goal-feasibility evaluation, heuristic asset allocation, and DQN-based strategy selection. A compact five-dimensional state representation encodes risk score, goal feasibility, equity allocation, savings rate, and financial runway. Trained on 3,000 episodes of synthetic data (seed=42), the final 100-episode mean reward improved 13.1\% over the training mean. Evaluation on 100 fixed scenarios showed the learned policy outperformed a heuristic baseline by 70.3\% in cumulative reward, 49.1\% in terminal balance, and 30 percentage points in goal on-track rate. These findings constitute simulation-based evidence that a compact RL policy can complement rule-based financial analysis; generalization to real-world settings requires further validation.
\keywords{Multi-Agent Systems, Reinforcement Learning, Personal Financial Planning, Asset Allocation, Explainable AI}
\end{abstract}
%
\section{Introduction}
%
Financial planning is central to long-term household stability and to goals such as retirement, education funding, and emergency preparedness. Although digital platforms now allow users to track balances, transactions, and investments with increasing granularity, many personal finance applications remain descriptive rather than prescriptive. They summarize spending and balances, but they do not adapt strategy as financial conditions change.

Traditional advisory systems rely on fixed heuristics, static risk questionnaires, or deterministic optimization rules. Such approaches are transparent but inflexible when user cash flow, market conditions, and goal feasibility evolve over time. Reinforcement learning offers a natural alternative by framing planning as sequential decision-making under uncertainty~\cite{betancourt2021drl,yang2023drl,cheng2024multiagent,li2024multiagent}. In finance, RL has been applied to portfolio allocation and risk-aware policy adaptation~\cite{lee2020maps,betancourt2021drl,yang2023drl,ma2023multiagent,cheng2024multiagent,li2024multiagent}, while interpretable variants expose the logic of learned policies~\cite{cong2021alpha,guan2021explainable}.

Most prior work targets portfolio management rather than holistic personal financial planning. The latter requires simultaneous reasoning about liquidity, runway, savings behavior, and goal feasibility—together with interfaces that users can understand. Work on robo-advising and explainable AI confirms that adoption depends on transparent explanation and preference alignment~\cite{alsabah2021robo,bendavid2021xai,bianchi2021robo,litty2024xai}.

This paper addresses that gap with a hybrid multi-agent framework integrating a rule-based Risk Agent, a simulation-based Goal Feasibility Agent, a heuristic Investment Allocation Agent, and a DQN-based Strategy Agent. These components produce a compact financial state representation over long-horizon simulated trajectories; a language-generation layer converts structured outputs into user-facing explanations. The contribution is architectural: RL is applied only at the strategy-selection layer of an otherwise rule-based pipeline, evaluated exclusively in a controlled synthetic environment.
%
\section{Literature Review}
%
\subsection{Overview}
The relevant literature spans three areas: RL-based portfolio management, robo-advisory systems, and explainability in financial AI. Portfolio-oriented RL shows that sequential decision methods adapt to changing market states~\cite{lee2020maps,betancourt2021drl,yang2023drl,ma2023multiagent,cheng2024multiagent,li2024multiagent}, while robo-advisory studies emphasize suitability and user acceptance~\cite{alsabah2021robo,bendavid2021xai,bianchi2021robo,litty2024xai,wang2021robo}. Explainability research argues that learned policies must remain interpretable to practitioners and end users~\cite{bendavid2021xai,cong2021alpha,guan2021explainable,bianchi2021robo,litty2024xai}. Personal financial planning sits at the intersection: it requires sequential adaptation, yet critical state variables extend beyond market returns to household liquidity, savings behavior, and goal progress.

\subsection{Research Gap}
Traditional digital advice maps risk questionnaires to model portfolios via auditable rules~\cite{alsabah2021robo,bianchi2021robo} but does not model cash-flow shocks, emergency liquidity, or deadline-constrained goals. ML-based methods adapt from observed choices~\cite{alsabah2021robo,wang2021robo} but remain investment-centric. Deep RL achieves strong portfolio results~\cite{lee2020maps,betancourt2021drl,yang2023drl,ma2023multiagent,cheng2024multiagent,li2024multiagent} but uses predominantly market-centric state representations~\cite{cong2021alpha,guan2021explainable}.

No prior work combines liquidity risk, savings behavior, and goal feasibility as explicit inputs to sequential strategy selection. The proposed framework bridges this gap: specialized analytical agents estimate these quantities, while DQN operates only at the strategy-selection layer, exposing intermediate financial metrics for auditing and explanation.

\section{Dataset}
All experiments use a synthetic financial planning dataset. Real-world longitudinal records combining income, expenses, liquid balances, asset allocation, and goal metadata are unavailable at the required granularity due to privacy and regulatory constraints; synthetic data provide a controlled basis for method development without exposing identifiable records.

