\section{Methodology}
The system follows a multi-agent architecture in which specialized components analyze complementary financial dimensions (Fig.~\ref{fig:flowchart}). The pipeline constructs a normalized state vector from profile, account, transaction, and goal data; selects a strategy action via DQN; and generates a natural-language report.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.1\textwidth]{Flowchart.png}
\caption{System architecture: structured user data feeds analytical agents, whose outputs form a normalized state vector for DQN strategy selection and language-based reporting.}
\label{fig:flowchart}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Risk Agent}
The Risk Agent estimates cash-flow fragility and liquidity capacity from recent transactions and liquid account balances. Burn rate is computed from recent debit transactions, monthly income from recent credits, and runway is defined as the ratio of liquid assets to monthly burn rate.

A normalized risk score is computed as a weighted combination of runway, stability ratio, and savings ratio:
\begin{equation}
\text{RiskScore} = 40 \cdot \text{norm}(\text{runway}) + 30 \cdot \text{norm}(\text{stability}) + 30 \cdot \text{savings\_ratio}
\end{equation}
Normalization bounds are set to $[0,12]$ months for runway and $[0.5, 2.0]$ for the stability ratio. The final score is clamped to the range $[0,100]$.

\subsection{Goal Feasibility Agent}
The Goal Feasibility Agent estimates whether financial goals are achievable under current savings behavior. A deterministic future value is first computed using current savings, monthly contributions, and an expected annual return of $7\%$.

Subsequently, $500$ Monte Carlo simulations are performed, where returns are sampled from a Gaussian distribution:
\begin{equation}
r \sim \mathcal{N}(0.07, 0.15^2)
\end{equation}

The success probability is defined as:
\begin{equation}
P_{\text{success}} = \frac{\text{Number of successful trajectories}}{500}
\end{equation}

Goals are categorized as:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textit{On-track} if $P_{\text{success}} \geq 0.75$
    \item \textit{At-risk} if $0.40 \leq P_{\text{success}} < 0.75$
    \item \textit{Unrealistic} otherwise
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Investment Allocation Agent}
The Investment Allocation Agent recommends a broad asset-class allocation across equity, debt, cash, and other assets. The allocation is heuristic and combines age-based equity rules, time-horizon adjustments, goal pressure, user risk appetite, capacity constraints derived from risk score, and macroeconomic adjustments.

The output includes a recommended allocation and may include an alternative allocation when there is a mismatch between risk capacity and stated risk appetite.

\subsection{Strategy Agent}

The Strategy Agent is the sole learned component, implemented as a Deep Q-Network (DQN) with two fully connected layers (64, 32 units, ReLU) and a five-unit output layer. The five discrete actions are: keep strategy, increase savings, reduce savings, shift to equity, and shift to bonds. The per-step reward is:
\begin{equation}
r_t = 0.01\,\Delta W - 2\,\mathbf{1}(R < 3) + 5\,\mathbf{1}(G) - 3\,\mathbf{1}(\neg G)
\label{eq:reward}
\end{equation}
where $\Delta W$ is the change in portfolio balance, $R$ is runway in months, and $G$ is a binary indicator of goal feasibility. The formulation rewards wealth growth, penalizes critically low liquidity ($R < 3$ months), and reinforces goal attainment. Each step corresponds to one simulated month.

\subsection{Explanation Layer}
The explanation layer converts structured agent outputs into a human-readable report using either an external large language model or a deterministic fallback. It operates post-hoc and is not part of the RL optimization. This design aligns with explainable financial AI and robo-advisory adoption research~\cite{bendavid2021xai,guan2021explainable,bianchi2021robo,litty2024xai}.

\section{Experimental Setup}

Training runs for 3,000 episodes in a synthetic environment; each episode samples a fresh financial profile and runs for 60--120 simulated monthly steps, exposing the agent to heterogeneous long-horizon trajectories. Four market regimes are modeled: normal ($\mu{=}7\%$, $\sigma{=}15\%$), bull ($12\%$, $12\%$), bear ($-5\%$, $20\%$), and recession ($-15\%$, $25\%$) annual equity returns; debt returns vary from $3\%$ to $4.5\%$ by regime. Income and expense shocks occur with 5\% monthly probability.

Hyperparameters: replay buffer 10{,}000; batch size 32; learning rate $10^{-3}$; discount $\gamma{=}0.99$; $\epsilon$ decaying from $1.0$ to $0.05$ ($\times0.995$ per episode); target-network update every 50 episodes. Seed 42 is fixed for both training and evaluation; multi-seed validation is left for future work.

