Table~\ref{tab:baseline} and Fig.~\ref{fig:baseline} compare the DQN against three baselines on 100 fixed evaluation scenarios. The DQN exceeds the heuristic in cumulative reward by 70.3\% and in terminal balance by 49.1\%, while raising the goal on-track rate by 30 percentage points—without degrading financial safety (low-runway rate 4\% vs.\ 5\%). Gains over the static keep-strategy and random baselines are substantially larger, underscoring the value of adaptive policy selection in the synthetic setting. These results are confined to the controlled simulation environment and do not imply real-world financial performance.

\subsection{Policy Behavior Analysis}

Within the simulation environment, the learned policy increases savings and reduces equity exposure when runway or goal feasibility deteriorates, and shifts toward higher equity allocation under stable conditions. This behavior is consistent with standard financial planning heuristics, suggesting the policy has internalized appropriate risk-adaptive responses in the synthetic setting (Figs.~\ref{fig:heatmap} and~\ref{fig:trajectory}).

