\section{Conclusion}

This paper presented a hybrid multi-agent framework coupling rule-based risk assessment, simulation-based goal analysis, heuristic asset allocation, and DQN-based strategy selection. The compact five-dimensional state vector shifts focus from market returns to household liquidity, savings behavior, and goal progress. In controlled synthetic experiments (seed=42, 3,000 training episodes), the DQN improved 13.1\% over the training mean and outperformed a heuristic baseline by 70.3\% in cumulative reward and 49.1\% in terminal balance across 100 evaluation scenarios.

These results constitute simulation-based architectural evidence, not validated real-world performance. Limitations include exclusive reliance on synthetic data, a single random seed, and the absence of transaction costs, taxes, or real-market dynamics. The contribution is methodological: demonstrating that rule-based financial analysis can be coupled with RL strategy selection in a reproducible, auditable prototype. The framework preserves interpretable intermediate outputs, consistent with explainable financial AI and robo-advisory research~\cite{bendavid2021xai,guan2021explainable,bianchi2021robo,litty2024xai}.

\subsection{Future Work}

Priority directions include multi-seed evaluation with confidence intervals; environments incorporating transaction costs, inflation, and tax effects; comparison with PPO and actor--critic methods; and external validation on privacy-preserving real-world datasets. Any practical deployment must incorporate data minimization, secure access controls, and clear regulatory positioning of outputs as decision support rather than financial advice.

